but I think implants
are way overrated.

243
00:12:07,794 --> 00:12:10,821
That's because your
breasts are excellent.

244
00:12:10,897 --> 00:12:14,095
Thank you. That's
exactly my point.

245
00:12:15,134 --> 00:12:16,363
Mine aren't huge,

246
00:12:16,436 --> 00:12:20,305
but every guy who's ever seen them
up close and personal has been thrilled.

247
00:12:21,007 --> 00:12:23,033
I definitely was.

248
00:12:23,109 --> 00:12:25,874
I am thrilled by every
part of your body.

249
00:12:28,581 --> 00:12:31,210
Sorry, my bad. Total TMI.

250
00:12:31,284 --> 00:12:33,981
I'm not even bothered
by your adenoidal voice.

251
00:12:34,053 --> 00:12:36,420
Except when you talk to
your mom on the phone.

252
00:12:36,489 --> 00:12:38,287
But I just put on headphones.

253
00:12:43,129 --> 00:12:46,827
At least you'll know he'll
be a totally honest boss.

254
00:12:53,106 --> 00:12:55,317
The incision is
extended superiorly

255
00:12:55,341 --> 00:12:58,020
to meet the atriotomy, and then
the interatrial septum is opened up.

256
00:12:58,044 --> 00:12:59,044
Retractor.

257
00:12:59,445 --> 00:13:02,472
A Carpentier retractor is used
to visualize the mitral valve.

258
00:13:02,915 --> 00:13:04,781
That will allow a
clear view of the tumor.

259
00:13:04,851 --> 00:13:06,080
Can we turn the channel?

260
00:13:06,152 --> 00:13:08,121
Color commentary's
getting a bit annoying.

261
00:13:08,187 --> 00:13:09,987
With the right
atrium opened obliq...

262
00:13:12,625 --> 00:13:15,094
How's Team Browne?
Any early standouts?

263
00:13:15,161 --> 00:13:17,494
Jackson's a bit
timid, but smart.

264
00:13:17,563 --> 00:13:19,930
Wolke is definitely
enthusiastic.

265
00:13:19,999 --> 00:13:22,764
And your star recruit is...

266
00:13:24,170 --> 00:13:26,105
pretty full of himself.

267
00:13:26,172 --> 00:13:28,505
I'm looking for surgeons,
and according to his recs,

268
00:13:28,574 --> 00:13:30,475
he can dissect and
suture like a pro.

269
00:13:30,977 --> 00:13:33,469
I thought you were
also looking for our input.

270
00:13:33,546 --> 00:13:35,640
He's ranked first by
every top program.

271
00:13:35,715 --> 00:13:38,116
You really think they're
all wrong and you're right?

272
00:13:40,887 --> 00:13:42,378
So, what brings
you all to the biz?

273
00:13:42,922 --> 00:13:45,255
Had my ACL
reconstructed in high school,

274
00:13:45,325 --> 00:13:47,157
both my rotators in college.

275
00:13:47,860 --> 00:13:51,854
I love the idea of fixing people,
helping them be the best they can be.

276
00:13:53,132 --> 00:13:55,601
Surgeons are the ones
with the God complex, right?

277
00:13:58,104 --> 00:13:59,231
I have that.

278
00:14:00,840 --> 00:14:03,605
I spent my life speaking
Yiddish and studying the Talmud

279
00:14:03,676 --> 00:14:05,338
and not shaving
the sides of my hair

280
00:14:05,411 --> 00:14:07,539
because someone up
there supposedly cares.

281
00:14:08,414 --> 00:14:10,042
But then I realized...

282
00:14:11,718 --> 00:14:12,879
no one's up there.

283
00:14:14,120 --> 00:14:15,486
No one cares.

284
00:14:16,189 --> 00:14:20,183
No benevolent higher power
is going to save us, so...

285
00:14:21,728 --> 00:14:23,162
we have to save each other.

286
00:14:26,165 --> 00:14:27,394
Can you top that?

287
00:14:27,467 --> 00:14:29,231
- Definitely not.
- Try anyway.

288
00:14:30,169 --> 00:14:32,764
You're obviously smart. You've
got two degrees from Harvard.

289
00:14:33,406 --> 00:14:36,205
My parents are Harvard alums,
so I'm sure that helped me get in.

290
00:14:36,275 --> 00:14:38,710
You're not gonna get hired
by undermining your own ex...

291
00:14:39,812 --> 00:14:41,075
Something went wrong.

292
00:14:41,514 --> 00:14:43,114
They nicked a pulmonary artery.

293
00:14:43,149 --> 00:14:44,777
If they had, Browne
would be suctioning,

294
00:14:44,851 --> 00:14:46,649
instead of Lim reaching
in with her hands.

295
00:14:51,591 --> 00:14:52,871
What are they doing now?

296
00:14:52,925 --> 00:14:53,925
Nothing.

297
00:14:54,794 --> 00:14:56,057
We can't access the tumor

298
00:14:56,129 --> 00:14:58,240
without compromising his
entire cardiac outflow tract.

299
00:14:58,264 --> 00:14:59,857
What about going in
the way I suggested?

300
00:14:59,932 --> 00:15:01,195
The median sternotomy.

301
00:15:01,267 --> 00:15:03,429
The tumor's too far back.
We need to close him up.

302
00:15:11,677 --> 00:15:14,511
Proton beam radiation
would be too toxic to the heart.

303
00:15:14,580 --> 00:15:16,344
Well, so is immunotherapy.

304
00:15:16,416 --> 00:15:18,578
We can't access the
entire tumor surgically,

305
00:15:18,651 --> 00:15:21,120
and we can't kill it without
killing his heart along with it.

306
00:15:21,521 --> 00:15:23,786
What if we cut out the
parts we can access

307
00:15:23,856 --> 00:15:26,416
and try our luck with
chemo on what's left?

308
00:15:26,926 --> 00:15:30,226
IV doxorubicin and ifosfamide
might slow the growth,

309
00:15:30,296 --> 00:15:31,389
give him a few more months.

310
00:15:31,464 --> 00:15:34,059
I'm not sending my patient
home with just a few extra months.

311
00:15:34,133 --> 00:15:35,260
It's better than nothing.

312
00:15:35,334 --> 00:15:37,530
- What about a transplant?
- Not an option.

313
00:15:37,603 --> 00:15:39,629
Heart tumors are
a contraindication.

314
00:15:40,239 --> 00:15:42,231
What if we transplant
his own heart?

315
00:15:42,775 --> 00:15:46,177
If we take it totally out of his chest,
we'd have access to the posterior heart.

316
00:15:46,245 --> 00:15:48,771
We could excise the tumor,
fix the defect left behind,

317
00:15:48,848 --> 00:15:49,848
and then put it back in.

318
00:15:49,916 --> 00:15:50,747
Cool.

319
00:15:50,817 --> 00:15:53,286
Not cool. At least with a
normal heart transplant,

320
00:15:53,352 --> 00:15:55,082
you'd be getting
a healthy heart.

321
00:15:55,154 --> 00:15:57,385
Her idea keeps the risk
of removing the heart

322
00:15:57,457 --> 00:15:59,756
and adds the risk that the
heart we'd be putting back in

323
00:15:59,826 --> 00:16:03,092
has just been severely compromised,
having had a tumor cut out of it.

324
00:16:03,162 --> 00:16:06,860
He's young, and the part of his
heart not infiltrated with tumor is strong.

325
00:16:09,635 --> 00:16:10,796
Do a cardiac MRA

326
00:16:10,870 --> 00:16:13,362
and see if the tumor's
infiltrated the coronary arteries.

327
00:16:13,439 --> 00:16:15,635
If it hasn't, Morgan's
idea could work.

328
00:16:15,708 --> 00:16:16,732
I'll schedule it.

329
00:16:19,512 --> 00:16:22,277
Dr. Murphy is dividing
the breast parenchyma

330
00:16:22,348 --> 00:16:23,646
into three pedicles.

331
00:16:24,283 --> 00:16:26,377
Anyone know where this
technique is derived from?

332
00:16:26,452 --> 00:16:28,011
Breast reduction surgery.

333
00:16:28,087 --> 00:16:29,111
That's right.

334
00:16:29,689 --> 00:16:33,057
And why would I use a
breast reduction technique

335
00:16:33,125 --> 00:16:34,991
to make the patient's
breasts larger?

336
00:16:35,061 --> 00:16:37,189
The technique
frees up the tissue.

337
00:16:37,897 --> 00:16:40,526
You can bring the pedicles
together to make the breasts smaller

338
00:16:40,600 --> 00:16:44,037
or spread them out over an
implant to make them larger.

339
00:16:45,238 --> 00:16:46,399
Very good.

340
00:16:46,472 --> 00:16:50,170
And now I'm going to turn the sound
off. Don't worry, nothing's wrong.

341
00:16:50,243 --> 00:16:53,008
I just wanna talk about you
behind your backs for a little bit.

342
00:16:55,548 --> 00:16:58,643
So first impressions. Murphy?

343
00:16:58,718 --> 00:17:00,550
I like Dr. John Lundberg.

344
00:17:01,254 --> 00:17:03,382
I haven't even
heard him speak yet.

345
00:17:03,456 --> 00:17:05,448
He has the highest USMLE scores.

346
00:17:05,525 --> 00:17:06,652
And that's important to you?

347
00:17:07,860 --> 00:17:12,423
Yes. It shows he has a
broad knowledge of medicine.

348
00:17:13,533 --> 00:17:15,525
What is important to you?

349
00:17:15,601 --> 00:17:18,901
Well, I'm more interested in what
they can do with their knowledge.

350
00:17:18,971 --> 00:17:21,770
Which is why, so far, I'm most
impressed with Jordan Allen.

351
00:17:22,241 --> 00:17:26,178
No. No. You said
she undermined you.

352
00:17:26,245 --> 00:17:27,406
Which takes courage

353
00:17:27,480 --> 00:17:30,040
and an assertiveness
that will serve her well.

354
00:17:30,583 --> 00:17:33,610
Then why did you tell
her to stop lecturing you?

355
00:17:34,086 --> 00:17:36,385
It's easier to teach an
aggressive resident restraint

356
00:17:36,455 --> 00:17:38,754
than a passive one
to assert themselves.

357
00:17:41,394 --> 00:17:43,260
How about you, Park?
What's important to you?

358
00:17:43,329 --> 00:17:46,561
I want to know who I can stand
to be around for 80 hours a week.

359
00:17:46,632 --> 00:17:49,295
One thing I learned as a cop,
you don't really know a person

360
00:17:49,368 --> 00:17:51,394
until you've had a
few drinks with them.

361
00:17:57,843 --> 00:17:59,744
LAD and circumflex look clean.

362
00:17:59,812 --> 00:18:04,147
What's with the right coronary?
It looks narrowed at the origin.

363
00:18:04,717 --> 00:18:06,913
It's a bit narrow, but
looks like a normal variant.

364
00:18:06,986 --> 00:18:08,249
Yeah, but it seems hazy,

365
00:18:08,321 --> 00:18:11,257
like there could be
some tumor infiltration.

366
00:18:12,425 --> 00:18:13,586
What do you guys think?

367
00:18:14,126 --> 00:18:16,357
- Us?
- Yeah. Come take a look.

368
00:18:19,665 --> 00:18:20,665
I guess...

369
00:18:20,700 --> 00:18:22,340
- It's angiogenesis of the left...
- Stop.

370
00:18:23,603 --> 00:18:27,165
Interrupting a female coworker is
almost as annoying as mansplaining.

371
00:18:27,239 --> 00:18:28,502
This isn't a rowing race.

372
00:18:28,574 --> 00:18:30,543
You don't always
have to speak first.

373
00:18:31,877 --> 00:18:35,871
I... do not love
the interruption.

374
00:18:37,450 --> 00:18:40,511
But... I like the enthusiasm.

375
00:18:42,254 --> 00:18:43,347
What were you gonna say?

376
00:18:44,957 --> 00:18:46,949
First, uh, I'm not sexist.

377
00:18:48,427 --> 00:18:49,520
Of course not.

378
00:18:50,129 --> 00:18:52,257
He's shifting from right-
to left-dominant circulation

379
00:18:52,331 --> 00:18:53,924
to feed blood to the tumor.

380
00:18:54,000 --> 00:18:55,332
- Angiogenesis.
- I doubt it.

381
00:18:55,401 --> 00:18:57,666
Surgery showed his tumor
extending to the right as well.

382
00:18:57,737 --> 00:18:59,000
What were you gonna say?

383
00:18:59,805 --> 00:19:02,206
The pulmonary artery is
right behind that vessel.

384
00:19:04,176 --> 00:19:06,839
It's causing radiographic
scatter in this area.

385
00:19:06,912 --> 00:19:10,110
The haze is just an artifact.
His arteries are clean.

386
00:19:11,717 --> 00:19:14,346
- I think she's right.
- Hmm.

387
00:19:16,555 --> 00:19:18,319
Your idea might just work.

388
00:19:22,828 --> 00:19:25,764
If you invert the sutures
and bury them under the skin,

389
00:19:25,831 --> 00:19:27,595
the scar will be invisible.

390
00:19:27,667 --> 00:19:29,533
No one will ever
know we were here.

391
00:19:31,937 --> 00:19:33,166
Nice work, both of you.

392
00:19:35,107 --> 00:19:36,837
Her BP's dropping.

393
00:19:36,909 --> 00:19:38,673
Push fluids, start IV pressors.

394
00:19:38,744 --> 00:19:41,873
Check for bleeding. She's in
V-tach. Move in the crash cart.

395
00:19:43,616 --> 00:19:45,517
No bleeding. No hematomas.

396
00:19:46,652 --> 00:19:49,087
Charging.

397
00:19:49,155 --> 00:19:50,179
Clear.

398
00:19:58,597 --> 00:20:01,066
Sinus rhythm. Her
BP is stabilizing.

399
00:20:03,903 --> 00:20:05,030
Get her to the ICU.

400
00:20:05,104 --> 00:20:07,335
I want post-op labs, CTA chest,

401
00:20:07,406 --> 00:20:09,375
and full 24-hour
cardiac telemetry.

402
00:20:10,509 --> 00:20:12,307
We need to figure out
what just happened.

403
00:20:19,819 --> 00:20:23,221
She's stable, but diffuse
delta wave slowing,

404
00:20:23,289 --> 00:20:24,689
minimal brain activity.

405
00:20:25,224 --> 00:20:28,854
An undiagnosed metabolic disorder
could've caused an adverse reaction

406
00:20:28,928 --> 00:20:29,987
to the anesthesia.

407
00:20:30,062 --> 00:20:31,724
Yeah, but her pre-op
labs were all normal.

408
00:20:31,797 --> 00:20:33,891
It's gotta be some sort
of hidden heart condition.

409
00:20:34,600 --> 00:20:37,297
You're big on opinions.
How are you with ideas?

410
00:20:37,369 --> 00:20:38,564
What would you do next?

411
00:20:40,673 --> 00:20:42,073
I'd check train-of-fours

412
00:20:42,141 --> 00:20:45,111
and reverse the
paralytics with neostigmine.

413
00:20:45,177 --> 00:20:47,373
If Dr. Murphy's right,
she should wake up.

414
00:20:47,446 --> 00:20:51,577
Smart. But risky. The
meds will stress her heart.

415
00:20:51,650 --> 00:20:53,778
If Park's right, she
could arrest again.

416
00:20:55,588 --> 00:20:58,251
I saw a similar case
last year in Borneo.

417
00:20:58,324 --> 00:21:00,816
- You interned at a hospital in Borneo?
- Uh, no.

418
00:21:00,893 --> 00:21:03,886
I volunteered at an
orangutan rescue foundation.

419
00:21:04,730 --> 00:21:08,064
Our guide, a local
villager, fell out of a tree.

420
00:21:08,134 --> 00:21:09,193
He was like 80 feet up.

421
00:21:09,268 --> 00:21:11,533
How is falling out
of a tree similar

422
00:21:11,604 --> 00:21:14,802
to a patient arresting during
breast reconstruction surgery?

423
00:21:14,874 --> 00:21:17,605
Well, he broke his back, but
when we got him to the hospital,

424
00:21:17,676 --> 00:21:19,838
I found he also had heart
damage from rheumatic fever

425
00:21:19,912 --> 00:21:22,973
and metabolic abnormality
from iodine deficiency.

426
00:21:23,616 --> 00:21:25,585
It's rare here, but
it's common there.

427
00:21:25,651 --> 00:21:28,052
We only realized it when we
ran a nuclear perfusion scan

428
00:21:28,120 --> 00:21:29,144
of his entire body.

429
00:21:29,822 --> 00:21:30,846
Good catch.

430
00:21:30,923 --> 00:21:34,519
But a scan that extensive
requires multiple radioactive tracers.

431
00:21:34,593 --> 00:21:36,113
You think her heart
could handle that?

432
00:21:36,762 --> 00:21:39,664
Not tonight. I'll get
consent from the mom.

433
00:21:40,499 --> 00:21:42,161
We'll do it first
thing in the morning.

434
00:21:42,735 --> 00:21:46,172
Once we confirm atrial closure,
we'll put the heart back in.

435
00:21:46,238 --> 00:21:49,902
Dr. Lim will reconnect the aorta
and the superior venous connections,

436
00:21:49,975 --> 00:21:51,671
while I connect the inferior.

437
00:21:51,744 --> 00:21:54,976
During my sub-internship, I
assisted on multiple heart transplants.

438
00:21:55,614 --> 00:21:57,054
Even sutured the
atrial cuff in one.

439
00:21:58,951 --> 00:22:01,147
I got to scrub in on a
liver transplant once.

440
00:22:01,787 --> 00:22:03,653
- The patient died.
- What'd you learn?

441
00:22:04,657 --> 00:22:07,491
That bile duct leaks are a lot
harder to detect than bleeds.

442
00:22:07,560 --> 00:22:10,189
Good. Next time I'd lead with
that instead of the patient's death.

443
00:22:14,533 --> 00:22:16,798
- Are you all done yet?
- Why?

444
00:22:16,869 --> 00:22:20,328
Dr. Park wants everyone
to join him in the break room.

445
00:22:27,146 --> 00:22:28,409
I'm Alex Park.

446
00:22:28,480 --> 00:22:31,473
I'm a former amateur
martial-arts competitor

447
00:22:31,550 --> 00:22:33,018
who once thought it'd be fun

448
00:22:33,085 --> 00:22:35,919
to spar with a pro boxer
visiting my dad's gym.

449
00:22:36,388 --> 00:22:39,187
And that guy was,
uh, Mike Tyson.

450
00:22:41,527 --> 00:22:43,359
Who's Mike Tyson?

451
00:22:43,896 --> 00:22:45,865
Uh, guy from <i>The Hangover.</i>

452
00:22:45,931 --> 00:22:48,162
With the tiger and
the tattoo on his face.

453
00:22:49,001 --> 00:22:51,869
Nice. You've just revealed
you're crazy and old.

454
00:22:55,574 --> 00:22:58,339
I've seen the musical
<i>Wicked</i> over 50 times.

455
00:22:58,410 --> 00:23:01,278
The San Francisco tryout,
Broadway, Chicago...

456
00:23:01,347 --> 00:23:04,078
I've even seen a friend's
boyfriend's niece play Glinda

457
00:23:04,149 --> 00:23:05,515
at Stagedoor summer camp.

458
00:23:06,385 --> 00:23:08,013
Nerd. Next.

459
00:23:12,558 --> 00:23:14,527
I'm Claire Browne. Um...

460
00:23:14,593 --> 00:23:18,428
I love music, but hate musicals.

461
00:23:18,497 --> 00:23:20,125
And, um, I don't...

462
00:23:20,532 --> 00:23:23,764
I don't really like to talk about
myself, so it's Shaun's turn, yeah.

463
00:23:30,476 --> 00:23:32,707
My name is Dr. Shaun Murphy.

464
00:23:32,778 --> 00:23:34,406
I used to not like music,

465
00:23:34,480 --> 00:23:37,609
but my girlfriend, Lea,
she changed my mind.

466
00:23:37,683 --> 00:23:41,381
I also like to watch the
Weather Channel on TV.

467
00:23:42,388 --> 00:23:43,412
And...

468
00:23:44,490 --> 00:23:47,426
ooh, I think pickles
are disgusting.

469
00:23:50,562 --> 00:23:53,464
Cops know how to manage up.
Managing down's another story.

470
00:23:53,532 --> 00:23:56,969
Well, he's mature, thoughtful,
doesn't have an ego.

471
00:23:57,836 --> 00:24:00,396
Neither does Murphy, but
do you think that qualifies him

472
00:24:00,472 --> 00:24:02,100
to supervise first-years?

473
00:24:02,841 --> 00:24:07,541
Well, Murphy's smart, brutally honest,
has no regard for social convention.

474
00:24:07,613 --> 00:24:09,741
- Hmm.
- It works for Bill Belichick.

475
00:24:11,183 --> 00:24:13,516
The Patriots are the most
corrupt, dishonest organization

476
00:24:13,585 --> 00:24:14,780
in the history of the NFL.

477
00:24:15,454 --> 00:24:16,786
Well, the Seahawks suck.

478
00:24:18,223 --> 00:24:20,317
So how's your
experience been here?

479
00:24:21,093 --> 00:24:22,652
It's been good.

480
00:24:26,165 --> 00:24:30,159
Did you consider any other
programs, or was this your first choice?

481
00:24:30,235 --> 00:24:32,636
This was my only choice.

482
00:24:33,372 --> 00:24:34,772
Why do you hate God?

483
00:24:35,975 --> 00:24:40,276
Oh. Uh, actually, I don't
believe there is a God.

484
00:24:41,513 --> 00:24:45,314
I thought maybe it was because
you believed he hated homosexuals.

485
00:24:46,352 --> 00:24:49,789
I don't think this is something that
we should be discussing at work.

486
00:24:49,855 --> 00:24:50,855
Mm.

487
00:24:52,391 --> 00:24:53,552
Why not?

488
00:24:55,761 --> 00:24:58,356
Well, because it's... personal.

489
00:25:01,834 --> 00:25:03,302
Do you have a boyfriend?

490
00:25:03,369 --> 00:25:06,635
